-- ── Grist ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Grist is an open-source, self-hostable spreadsheet with database powers, combining familiar spreadsheet editing with relational data, formulas and a REST API.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (open-source self-hosted plus per-user cloud subscriptions)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted or cloud Free plan); paid plans from $10/user/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Grist Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Grist review covering the open-source spreadsheet-database hybrid, self-hosting options, Free, Pro, Business and Enterprise pricing, pros, cons for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Grist is an open-source spreadsheet-database hybrid built by Grist Labs, a small, deliberately self-funded software company based in New York City. Grist Labs was founded in 2014 by brothers Dmitry and Stan Sagalovskiy; Dmitry had already co-founded Hudson River Trading, a high-frequency trading firm, in 2002, and the New York Math Circle, an educational non-profit, in 2008, giving the founding team both deep technical credibility and a track record of building durable, mission-driven organizations before starting Grist Labs. According to the company's own account, Grist Labs was founded not long after the 2013 Snowden mass-surveillance disclosures revealed how vulnerable even reputable cloud services could be, and the founders concluded that the best remedy available to them was open-source code, transparent security practices, and giving users the option to run their own infrastructure rather than trusting a closed, remote service by default. That founding philosophy shaped Grist's entire product and business strategy: rather than raising venture capital and optimizing for growth at any cost, Grist Labs has remained self-funded throughout its history, and the company later open-sourced Grist itself, releasing the core grist-core engine along with grist-desktop and grist-static under the Apache License, Version 2.0, so that any individual or organization can run a full Grist instance on their own servers with no dependency on Grist Labs' hosted service. As of the mid-2020s Grist Labs remains a small, distributed team of roughly a dozen to several dozen people spread across North America, Europe and Africa, deliberately staying lean relative to the size of its user base. Product-wise, Grist occupies a distinct niche between conventional spreadsheets like Excel or Google Sheets and full relational databases like Airtable or Postgres-backed no-code tools. It looks and feels like a spreadsheet, with a familiar grid interface, formulas and instant editing, but under the hood every Grist document is backed by a real relational data model, meaning tables can be properly linked to each other, data types are enforced, and large datasets stay fast and reliable in ways that traditional spreadsheets struggle with once they grow past a few thousand rows. On top of that data layer, Grist adds features associated with no-code application builders: customizable views and widgets (grid, card, chart and other layouts over the same underlying data), page layouts that can be assembled into lightweight internal tools, granular access control that can restrict permissions down to specific rows, columns or even individual cells, formulas written in real Python rather than a proprietary spreadsheet formula language, a REST API for programmatic access, and, more recently, an AI Assistant that can help users write formulas, clean data or build new views using natural language. Grist's pricing is split cleanly between a self-hosted, fully open-source path and a cloud-hosted, per-user subscription path, and both are actively maintained. The self-hosted Community Edition is completely free and open source, downloadable from GitHub, with community-only support, making it a natural fit for privacy-conscious individuals, nonprofits or organizations with existing infrastructure. The cloud-hosted Free plan is also 0 dollars per user per month and includes up to 5,000 records per document, a lifetime allotment of 100 AI Assistant credits, and support for up to two guests per document. The Pro plan costs 10 dollars per user per month, or 8 dollars per user per month when billed annually (a 20 percent discount), and raises the per-document record limit to 100,000, adds three years of document snapshot history, and increases the AI Assistant allotment to 100 credits per month along with support for unlimited documents. The Business plan costs 30 dollars per user per month, or 24 dollars per user per month billed annually, requires a minimum of five users, and further raises limits to 150,000 records per document, five years of snapshot history, 2,000 AI Assistant credits per month, workflow automations and priority email support. An Enterprise plan, available both cloud-hosted and self-hosted, is custom priced and adds advanced customization, dedicated servers in a chosen region, custom SSO and domain branding, audit log streaming and deeper administrative controls, with self-hosted Enterprise customers additionally getting priority support and access to pre-release security updates. Grist Labs also offers a 50 percent discount on the Pro plan for registered nonprofits, and organizations with less than 1 million dollars in annual revenue can request free activation of paid features. Grist's closest competitors are Airtable, Baserow, NocoDB and, to a lesser extent, Google Sheets and Excel for teams that eventually outgrow a pure spreadsheet, and it differentiates itself primarily through its combination of a fully open-source, self-hostable core, Python-based formulas instead of a proprietary formula language, cell-level access control, and a self-funded, privacy-first company culture that has deliberately avoided the venture-capital-driven growth pressure common among its no-code database competitors.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'b0a59332-e7cb-4428-afe9-3934017982dd';

